\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.1}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Principle of the experiment.} (a) Atomic levels and laser coupling scheme. A $\pi $-polarized light beam tuned within the hyperfine structure of the ${^1\mathrm  {S}_0} \rightarrow {^3\mathrm  {P}_1}$~transition (red arrows) creates an energy shift in the electronic ground state, with significant tensor component $U_{TLS}(m_F) = q \, m_F^2$. A second laser (here $\sigma ^-$ polarized) enables Raman transitions. Thanks to the tensor light shift, the Raman resonance conditions differ from each other, making it possible to drive Rabi oscillations between two isolated spin states (here $\mathinner {|{-5/2}\rangle }$ and $\mathinner {|{-7/2}\rangle }$), all other processes being off-resonant. The Raman operation can be understood as a rotation in a sub-Bloch sphere. A potential linear energy shift $U_{linear}(m_F) = b \, m_F$ (in the illustration, $b \simeq - 3 q$) does not directly affect the capacity to isolate a pair of states. (b) The three experimental schemes in this paper. Top: We operate a Ramsey interferometer between states $\mathinner {|{-5/2}\rangle }$ and $\mathinner {|{-7/2}\rangle }$, decoupled from the other spin states. Middle: We operate two interferometers in parallel, demonstrating multi-parameter simultaneous sensing of the fields acting on the atoms. Bottom: we characterize the collective state of atoms in a superposition of two Zeeman levels ($\mathinner {|{-5/2}\rangle }$ and $\mathinner {|{-7/2}\rangle }$), identified as qubit states. The measurement sequence starts by applying two pulses that map the populations of the qubit states into ancillary states. Combining this with a final rotation in the qubit sub-Bloch-sphere, one can simultaneously measure two orthogonal components of the pseudo-spin of the ensemble of qubits.}}{10}{figure.caption.42}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:fig1}{{2.1}{10}{\textbf {Principle of the experiment.} (a) Atomic levels and laser coupling scheme. A $\pi $-polarized light beam tuned within the hyperfine structure of the \RedMotTransition ~transition (red arrows) creates an energy shift in the electronic ground state, with significant tensor component $U_{TLS}(m_F) = q \, m_F^2$. A second laser (here $\sigma ^-$ polarized) enables Raman transitions. Thanks to the tensor light shift, the Raman resonance conditions differ from each other, making it possible to drive Rabi oscillations between two isolated spin states (here $\ket {-5/2}$ and $\ket {-7/2}$), all other processes being off-resonant. The Raman operation can be understood as a rotation in a sub-Bloch sphere. A potential linear energy shift $U_{linear}(m_F) = b \, m_F$ (in the illustration, $b \simeq - 3 q$) does not directly affect the capacity to isolate a pair of states. (b) The three experimental schemes in this paper. Top: We operate a Ramsey interferometer between states $\ket {-5/2}$ and $\ket {-7/2}$, decoupled from the other spin states. Middle: We operate two interferometers in parallel, demonstrating multi-parameter simultaneous sensing of the fields acting on the atoms. Bottom: we characterize the collective state of atoms in a superposition of two Zeeman levels ($\ket {-5/2}$ and $\ket {-7/2}$), identified as qubit states. The measurement sequence starts by applying two pulses that map the populations of the qubit states into ancillary states. Combining this with a final rotation in the qubit sub-Bloch-sphere, one can simultaneously measure two orthogonal components of the pseudo-spin of the ensemble of qubits}{figure.caption.42}{}}
